[
    {
        "content": "<p>Following the advice of <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"275920\">@John Baez</span> to ask many --potentially stupid-- questions: Is there some sense in which we can view a category of functors that have adjoints as a dagger category wherein the dagger corresponds to taking the left/right adjoint of the functor? If so, does this mean that a dagger category is a generalisation of adjointed functors or that adjoint functors are some sort of 'categorization' of dagger categories?</p>",
        "id": 225459908,
        "sender_full_name": "John van de Wetering",
        "timestamp": 1612697924
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>To muse a bit about this, if it is true, then monads are precisely the <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>†</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\dagger</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">†</span></span></span></span>-positive maps, and the unitaries are precisely the adjoint equivalences</p>",
        "id": 225459933,
        "sender_full_name": "John van de Wetering",
        "timestamp": 1612697996
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>A compact closed category, seen as a bicategory with a single 0-cell, is a bicategory whose morphisms all have adjoints (the duals) and left&amp;right adjoints are isomorphic, so that would be the \"best case\" where the operation of taking adjoints is most similar to a dagger. You can start by asking yourself whether you are happy with this being a kind of dagger-bicategory.</p>",
        "id": 225468518,
        "sender_full_name": "Amar Hadzihasanovic",
        "timestamp": 1612711097
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In fact I think that historically the opposite has happened: dagger categories were invented as a framework to talk about dualities that are <em>not</em> expressible by properties in the language of \"bare\" category theory, such as the duality induced by a choice of adjoints.</p>",
        "id": 225468629,
        "sender_full_name": "Amar Hadzihasanovic",
        "timestamp": 1612711212
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So of your two options I think \"dagger categories are a generalisation\" is closer to the truth.</p>",
        "id": 225468788,
        "sender_full_name": "Amar Hadzihasanovic",
        "timestamp": 1612711406
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"296293\">@John van de Wetering</span> wrote:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>If so, does this mean that a dagger category is a generalisation of adjointed functors or that adjoint functors are some sort of 'categorization' of dagger categories?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I've only seen this in special case.  The main problem is that taking the dagger of a morphism twice in a dagger category gets you back to the same morphism, whereas taking the left adjoint of a functor twice (if you can) may not, and ditto for the right adjoint.  </p>\n<p>However, there are some functors whose left adjoint is also their right adjoint:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/ambidextrous+adjunction\">Ambidextrous adjunction</a>.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>These tend to show up a lot in representation theory: for example if G and H are finite groups and Rep(G) and Rep(H) are their categories of representations, any homomorphism f : G <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>→</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\to</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.36687em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span></span></span></span> H gives a functor <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>f</mi><mo>∗</mo></msub><mo>:</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f_\\ast:</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.175696em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-left:-0.10764em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mbin mtight\">∗</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span></span></span></span> Rep(H) <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>→</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\to</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.36687em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span></span></span></span> Rep(G) in an obvious way, and this always has an ambidextrous adjoint.  In the literature on group representation theory this fact is called <strong>Frobenius reciprocity</strong>.</p>\n<p>This is a special case of a more general thing: any morphism between <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/Kapranov-Voevodsky+2-vector+space\">Kapranov--Voevodsky 2-vector spaces</a> has an ambidextrous adjoint.</p>\n<p>The name sounds scary, but a <strong>KV 2-vector space</strong> is just a category equivalent to <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">V</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">c</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">t</mi></mrow><mi>n</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{Vect}^n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.748732em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\" style=\"margin-right:0.01389em;\">V</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">c</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">t</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.748732em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.1473400000000002em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> for some <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span></span></span></span>.   A morphism between them is an exact <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">V</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">c</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{Vect}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\" style=\"margin-right:0.01389em;\">V</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">c</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">t</span></span></span></span></span>-enriched functor, and a 2-morphism is a natural transformation.</p>\n<p>So, the 2-category of KV 2-vector spaces is a kind of categorification of a dagger category, where taking the adjoint of a 1-morphism acts like a dagger.</p>",
        "id": 225475327,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1612720554
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Returning to the larger question, I think you have to choose what you're interested in:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>2-categories where every morphism has a left adjoint </li>\n<li>2-categories where every morphism has a right adjoint</li>\n<li>2-categories where every morphism has a left adjoint, and, separately, a right adjoint</li>\n<li>2-categories where every morphism has an ambidextrous adjoint: a morphism that's both a left adjoint and right adjoint</li>\n<li>dagger 2-categories.</li>\n</ul>",
        "id": 225475767,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1612721281
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The last may not have been defined yet - but the second to last has been, and it should be a special case of the last.</p>",
        "id": 225475816,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1612721324
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>A \"dagger 2-category\" would be a 2-category with some extra <em>structure</em> specifying the dagger of every 1-morphism.   </p>\n<p>A 2-category where every morphism has an ambidextrous adjoint should be a special case, but this is a 2-category with an extra <em>property</em>, so it's nicer.</p>",
        "id": 225475885,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1612721426
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276363\">Amar Hadzihasanovic</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/Categorical.20adjoints.20as.20dagger.20category/near/225468629\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>In fact I think that historically the opposite has happened: dagger categories were invented as a framework to talk about dualities that are <em>not</em> expressible by properties in the language of \"bare\" category theory, such as the duality induced by a choice of adjoints.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>That makes a lot of sense, thanks!</p>",
        "id": 225477789,
        "sender_full_name": "John van de Wetering",
        "timestamp": 1612723760
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"275920\">John Baez</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/Categorical.20adjoints.20as.20dagger.20category/near/225475327\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>The name sounds scary, but a <strong>KV 2-vector space</strong> is just a category equivalent to <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">V</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">c</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">t</mi></mrow><mi>n</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{Vect}^n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.748732em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\" style=\"margin-right:0.01389em;\">V</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">c</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">t</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.748732em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.1473400000000002em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> for some <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span></span></span></span>.   A morphism between them is an exact <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">V</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">c</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{Vect}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\" style=\"margin-right:0.01389em;\">V</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">c</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">t</span></span></span></span></span>-enriched functor, and a 2-morphism is a natural transformation.</p>\n<p>So, the 2-category of KV 2-vector spaces is a kind of categorification of a dagger category, where taking the adjoint of a 1-morphism acts like a dagger</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>With <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">V</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">c</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">t</mi></mrow><mi>n</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{Vect}^n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.748732em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\" style=\"margin-right:0.01389em;\">V</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">c</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">t</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.748732em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.1473400000000002em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> do you mean <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span></span></span></span> copies of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">V</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">c</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{Vect}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\" style=\"margin-right:0.01389em;\">V</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">c</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">t</span></span></span></span></span>?</p>",
        "id": 225477864,
        "sender_full_name": "John van de Wetering",
        "timestamp": 1612723849
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The phrase \"Dagger 2-category\" could be taken to mean two different things, depending on whether you want there to be a dagger on 1-cells or on 2-cells. An example of the former should  be given by bicategories of spans (and presumably by 2-categories where every 1-cell has an ambidextrous adjoint etc), whereas an example of the latter is given by DagCat, the 2-category of (small) dagger categories, dagger functors and natural transformations: it turns out that that taking the dagger pointwise of a natural transformation between dagger functors results in a natural transformation. I've usually seen the phrase dagger 2-category to mean the latter notion (so having a dagger on 2-cells): this appears not just in  papers I'm involved in, but also in some further works building on these, such as in the recent <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2101.05210\">https://arxiv.org/abs/2101.05210</a> .</p>",
        "id": 225479798,
        "sender_full_name": "Martti Karvonen",
        "timestamp": 1612726336
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>As far as the original question goes, I have nothing to add to what other said, but I'll turn the question on its head: it's also been asked if the daggers of linear maps (i.e. adjoints) are adjunctions in a suitable category. A positive answer of sorts is given in <a href=\"https://www.jstor.org/stable/2040415?seq=1\">https://www.jstor.org/stable/2040415?seq=1</a> : roughly speaking, a bounded linear map  between Hilbert spaces and its adjoint induce a (contravariant) adjunction between the lattices of closed subspaces, and up to scalars all adjunctions between the subspace lattices are of this form.</p>",
        "id": 225480026,
        "sender_full_name": "Martti Karvonen",
        "timestamp": 1612726719
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"296293\">John van de Wetering</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/Categorical.20adjoints.20as.20dagger.20category/near/225477864\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>With <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">V</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">c</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">t</mi></mrow><mi>n</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{Vect}^n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.748732em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\" style=\"margin-right:0.01389em;\">V</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">c</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">t</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.748732em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.1473400000000002em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> do you mean <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span></span></span></span> copies of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">V</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">c</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{Vect}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\" style=\"margin-right:0.01389em;\">V</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">c</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">t</span></span></span></span></span>?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I mean the n-fold product of categories <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">V</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">c</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">t</mi></mrow><mo>×</mo><mo>⋯</mo><mo>×</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">V</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">c</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">t</mi></mrow></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{Vect} \\times \\cdots \\times \\mathsf{Vect}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.77777em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\" style=\"margin-right:0.01389em;\">V</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">c</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">t</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.66666em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"minner\">⋯</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\" style=\"margin-right:0.01389em;\">V</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">c</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">t</span></span></span></span></span>.   Just as every finite-dimensional vector space is isomorphic to <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">F</mi><mi>n</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{F}^n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68889em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">F</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.664392em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> where <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">F</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{F}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68889em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">F</span></span></span></span></span> is your chosen field, every KV 2-vector space is equivalent to  <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">V</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">c</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">t</mi></mrow><mi>n</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{Vect}^n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.748732em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\" style=\"margin-right:0.01389em;\">V</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">c</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">t</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.748732em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.1473400000000002em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>.   Just as morphisms between finite-dimensional vector spaces can be described using matrices, morphisms between KV 2-vector spaces can be described using matrices of vector spaces.  So it's all a straightforward categorification.</p>",
        "id": 225484270,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1612732676
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"277285\">Martti Karvonen</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/Categorical.20adjoints.20as.20dagger.20category/near/225480026\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>As far as the original question goes, I have nothing to add to what other said, but I'll turn the question on its head: it's also been asked if the daggers of linear maps (i.e. adjoints) are adjunctions in a suitable category. A positive answer of sorts is given in <a href=\"https://www.jstor.org/stable/2040415?seq=1\">https://www.jstor.org/stable/2040415?seq=1</a> : roughly speaking, a bounded linear map  between Hilbert spaces and its adjoint induce a (contravariant) adjunction between the lattices of closed subspaces, and up to scalars all adjunctions between the subspace lattices are of this form.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Hmm, This actually feels quite close to some stuff we have done in effectus theory, where for every map <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span></span></span></span> we can define 'possibilistic' maps <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>f</mi><mo>⋄</mo></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f_\\diamond</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.16111499999999998em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-left:-0.10764em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mbin mtight\">⋄</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>f</mi><mo>⋄</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f^\\diamond</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.674115em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mbin mtight\">⋄</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> between the posets of sharp predicates (in opposite directions) that are Galois connections. I'll need to see if this stuff is indeed related somehow.</p>",
        "id": 225545576,
        "sender_full_name": "John van de Wetering",
        "timestamp": 1612791892
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Indeed, looking at this more closely, it looks like  a special case  of Corollary 208VII in <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/1803.01911\">Bas Westerbaan's thesis</a>, and his statement that the adjunction characterises a linear map up to scalar is a property called 'rigidity' in the context of von Neumann algebras in <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/1804.02203\">Bram Westerbaan's thesis</a>, Section 4.1.5.</p>",
        "id": 225547753,
        "sender_full_name": "John van de Wetering",
        "timestamp": 1612792918
    }
]